About:
I am the ghostliest Puerto Rican/Roman Italian you will ever meet... I am an ENTJ on the MBTI. I'm not super fond of people unless they are intelligent and trustworthy, or AT LEAST somewhat good looking or useful in one way or another (superficial yet deep- just don't let the looks run out). What can I say? I appreciate brains and beauty; one or the other; both is ideal.  I keep a small ring of close friends, the rest are pretty much expendable; useful as pawns to an end, and I like it that way. It takes a bit of work to earn my trust and friendship, and though I am quick to make acquaintances and connections, I am just as quick to shed them if they are not productive. I like to get returns on my investments, and this includes time with people. Don't waste my time. You won't be happy with what I take in return. I can be your best friend or your worst enemy. I tend not to be a very ideological or idealistic person so as to remain objective. I can be bit of a misanthrope, and I judge very quickly and harshly, so never ask me my thoughts unless you want an honest answer and are prepared to have your ideas dissected and handed back to you in pieces.  
You will probably come to the conclusion that I am either stupid, very mean, very smart, negative, funny or friendly as this is what I am often told. Charming right? I can be if need be. You probably would recognize me as in touch with humanity until I choose to let it fall apart- then my friend YOU would see what we are all truly made of in our hearts (insert evil laughter here).

***If I've offended you*** 
I'm very sorry, I assure you it wasn't my intention :x 
I always debate on whether I should actually put something meaningful here or just put something witty; but seeing as this is a website for personality types I guess I should tell you a bit about me :) 
Well, I love personality typing. In fact it was my trying to find out more about myself that I learned about the Myers-Briggs test and found out about the types. Originally I tested as an ENFP but I later realized that I was answering based on what I *wished* I was, not how I actually felt. 
So, turns out I'm an INFJ (only slightly more so than INTJ). I feel like I fit in much better with my profile now :) 
I'm pretty much textbook INFJ, but I wouldn't say I'm as warm and nurturing as most others seem, which worries me sometimes. Im sarcastic, I like to play games of wit, and occasionally enjoy messing with people. Maybe it's because I have trouble being warm with others when I know how much they're dishonest with me, or I feel scorned by them (it's hard for me to let things go). I can be very nurturing and protective towards animals (and plants even, I view them as my little essences of pure life, because of how simple they are) but I'm also very realistic. I think its because of my thinking/feeling borderline. 
My feelings towards humanity, at first, are with pessimism and borderline disgust. Humans are so complicated, mean, selfish. Myself included. 
But just when I wish I could write humans off as something I dislike I think of the amazing people I know, who are kind, warm, and genuinely good. Then I'm forced to see humanity as simply having a great capacity for both good and evil, if you think of things in terms or good and evil, but that's a whole other topic of my philosophy ;)

I know what the caged bird feels, alas! 
When the sun is bright on the upland slopes; 
When the wind stirs soft through the springing grass, 
And the river flows like a stream of glass; 
When the first bird sings and the first bud opes, 
And the faint perfume from its chalice steals-- 
I know what the caged bird feels! 
I know why the caged bird beats his wing 
Till its blood is red on the cruel bars; 
For he must fly back to his perch and cling 
When he fain would be on the bough a-swing; 
And a pain still throbs in the old, old scars 
And they pulse again with a keener sting-- 
I know why he beats his wing! 
I know why the caged bird sings, ah me, 
When his wing is bruised and his bosom sore,-- 
When he beats his bars and he would be free; 
It is not a carol of joy or glee, 
But a prayer that he sends from his heart's deep core, 
But a plea, that upward to Heaven he flings-- 
I know why the caged bird sings!   
Paul Laurence Dunbar

As for the personality aspects of my life, I left my home town at 13, and my next town at 19, and wish I had kept in contact with friends.

Sometimes  i look at my life like a TV show, with episodes in which I did something random and different every time. 
I liked early PC gaming, then i became a bit of a socialite and stopped playing. I've spent time living on a camp site by the beach and earning a free stay working in their cafe, I play the guitar but i love both instrumental & electronic music, i learned capoeira & breakdancing from an Indian guy in exchange for being an actor for a play he'd written at a local theatre, then i set up my own weekly event at a local nightclub and ran that for a year before moving it to a better club which some of my friends had acquired, but eventually i found myself waiting tables for a few years before joining the claims department of a car insurance company. I worked there for several years and worked up to fraud department in a position they created for me. I loved it but then i was diagnosed with ME/CFS and couldn't work anymore. Slowly but surely it went from mild to severe and loads of other health problems began to fall on top of me. 
I'm still housebound but i make it a point of principle to summon every ounce of my being to take a holiday abroad every couple of years (whenever i can afford the money and have the strength). My two ambitions in life are A) to ensure I don't die before my parents, and B) find a way to make money and move to a coastal area in a country with a tropical climate (hot & humid), like maybe Costa Rica. :)

I enjoy a challenge and long for the thrill of excitement and risk. I love people, viewing everyone and everything as part of an often extraordinary, interconnected whole. I see patterns and connections in everything. I am naturally inclined toward forming relationships with people and animals. Intense emotional experiences vital to a life of substance and I seek harmonious relationships with others and within myself. 
Some might say that I am a human guinea pig because I love to experiment on myself and with life. I am a risk taker and extremely bold! When I want something in life, I go for it. I am never afraid of taking the plunge, especially if there?s risk involved. I don?t shy away from speaking my mind in some way. Everything I do is carefully and critically calculated in my mind beforehand. It is almost as if, I am rehearsing a script with different endings in my head and I?ll try each one to see what works. I live life as it should be lived: with total enthusiasm and challenge what I fear most. 
I am unpredictably spontaneous, charismatic with a great deal of amusingly unconventional attributes. I do gain the favor of the more straitlaced individuals because in spite of my nonconformity, I am warm, affectionate, outgoing, fun, and genuinely like people. I enjoy telling stories, especially funny stories about my family and friends. If you want the world to know something, just tell me. Perfection is an illusion that I don?t buy into. Close enough is often all right with me, which may unnerve more precise thinking types. I become closer to perfection each day but even I know that absolute truth or absolute perfection does not exist because we are in a constant state of change for better or for worse- till death do we part. 
I make a good first impression. I am mature and playful, these two sides to my personality are constantly dueling it out. Part of me likes all of the finer things in life, while part of me is just like a big kid. No matter what side I choose, I am always adventurous and dramatic. I take life by the horns. I am up for fun of all kinds, and it?s hard for me to say no to a good time. I tend to go until I drop. I am outgoing and engaging, with both strangers and friends. I truly enjoy being with people and bring energy into any situation. Enthusiastic and fun, I am the first to say, ?let?s go?! 
My attention span can be short often being easily intrigued and distracted by new friends and acquaintances, forgetting about the older ones for long stretches at a time. Everyone doesn?t have to believe that I am wonderful and fascinating person. Humility? I don?t have much to be humble about! And I might as well promote myself, because no one else will. I believe that I am a pretty special person and I let everyone know about it. As long as it is true, I will let my colors shine. I am learning not to pretend to be confident within areas that I am insecure. That is a death trap. Be proud about being who you are, sure it?s alright to fake it till you make it, but be honest with yourself when things don?t work out. 
I am conscientiousness; generally good at balancing work and play, when I need to buckle down, I can usually get tasks done. But I?ve been known to goof off when I know I can get away with it. Overall my life is relatively smooth, I remain cool and collected, but sometimes I do panic; there are a few rides on the emotional roller coaster that I would like to eliminate. My self-interest overrules and others come later when I am not able to function with my A game. To Be True to Thy Own Self is the most important task I intend to successfully master. I want to know exactly who I am and exactly who God is. How can we have a relationship if we don?t even know each other. This is a mind blowing mystery to me. There are far too many riddles to solve and not enough clues. Each time I think I figure it out, I am quickly starting back from Go again with no $200 dollars. I want out. I want to escape this trap I am caught in.
Yet to be fulfilled

He drew a circle that shut me out ?
Heretic, rebel, a thing to flout.
But Love and I had the wit to win:
We drew a circle that took him in. 
?Outwitted, Edwin Markham

I'm a massive twat. You should love me.

I was born on the 4th of July, four years before the century, the fourth child of eight: four boys and four girls. I was named Elizabeth so that my parents could call me Ellie. See, we have a tradition in our family to name the kids one thing and call them by another name that has to end with an ee sound. Before me was William (Billy), Ruth (Ruthie), and Gennifer (Gennie). After me came Edmond (Eddie), Jonathan (Jonny), Grace (Gracie), and James (Jimmy). We also have a cat, Kitty, who came when Gracie was a baby. 
When I was a baby, I was either very, very happy, or very, very un-happy. Rarely was I calm or just content, except in my baby swing. This character trait has continued to this day. Im either hyper, happy, and bubbly, or Im depressed, moody, and angry. (Or, Im in a zone, and if Im in a zone, God help the person who interrupts me. Fair warning, dont interrupt me on the piano.) Rarely am I someone in between happy and sad. Does that make me bi-polar? Ill have to look that up. Ive wondered before if I have some kind of personality disorder. But in my honest opinion! I dont think some of these disorders should be called disorders, theyre just personalities. I dont like labels and boxes. I hate being told what to do or who I am. A friend asked me recently (very politely) if I might have a bit of ADD or ADHD. I dont. I think a lot of kids with ADD and ADHD really dont have a disorder problem, they have a discipline problem. Spank that kid and make him happy! Of course, thats only true in some cases. But I digress. I dont have ADD, but I must be moving to pay attention to, say, a sermon or a seminar. I actually dont have to be moving, but I need my eyes focused on something. I usually doodle. Occasionally I take notes. Sometimes I will make a cloud of words by just scribbling whatever word the speaker is saying at that time. Sometimes Ill trace my finger along something back and forth. I just need something, otherwise I will begin to daydream. Doodling doesnt mean I wont daydream, but not doodling (or something of the sort) means I certainly will! 
But I dont think I have a personality disorder. I am kind of crazy though, or people tell me I am. Why am I crazy? Does everyone have these crazy thoughts and feel like saying crazy things? I bet Im not crazy, Im just brave. Ill say things were ALL thinking! Ha! So you are crazy too! I like to think that anyway. 
Im not always crazy though, sometimes Im just plain, straight-up awkward! 
Okay, heres the actual truth. Sometimes Im a genius, sometimes Im a clutz. Sometimes Im hilarious, sometimes Im just sweet and sensitive. Sometimes I reply super quickly and say the most embarrassing things, sometimes Im more thoughtful. Sometimes Im outgoing, sometimes Im shy and very quiet. Some people say Im brilliant and a deep thinker, some people say Im shallow and naive. How can I be all of those things? Because Im a responder. I react differently to different people. Its the strangest thing. Sometimes just by the way they nod their head or phrase a question, I can feel words bubble up or simmer down. I can know two people of the same personality type and be able to communicate with only one. 
Understand, I am not being fake. Its a natural reaction. If I tried to act the same around everyone, then I would be fake. I read this on an ENFP description once. My personality type is that of an ENFP. 
See, I told you I didnt like labels, but I lied. Im a walking contradiction, and in a few moments Ill tell you why that isnt true either. First though, let me say that I love reading ENFP descriptions because I feel a deep part of me resound with the feeling of not being alone. Also, while I act different around everyone and every group, eventually, when Ive been friends with someone long enough, I find myself acting with them like I act with my siblings at home. When they still love me, I know Ive found a best friend. 
Okay, so do I contradict myself? No. I mean yes, but I dont contradict some things. I have values, morals, and mindsets that are firm. There are certain values, and I didnt choose them myself, that I cant compromise. Among those are: loyalty to friends, availability to those in need, general kindness to every person, individuality, thinking the best of every new person I meet, loving someone for who they are and like they are. I can honestly say that if I have bad feelings toward anyone, it doesnt ever settle well, ever. In general, I like people, all of them. And if I find myself disliking someone, it weighs heavy. I hate the feeling and have to get rid of it. I do. 
Yeah, thats just a few details about me. I have more, but I already lost interest in this bio.

You're an extrovert, energised by the presence of other people and you're probably not afraid to take risks.Negatives: Last-borns tend to get bored quickly. They may harbour unrealistic expectations of finding a relationship that is always fun - and of course, such relationships simply do not last.Babies of the family are social and outgoing, they are the most financially irresponsible of all birth orders. They just want to have a good time. Knowing that these kids love the limelight, it's no surprise to discover that Billy Crystal, Goldie Hawn, Drew Carey, Jim Carey and Steve Martin are all lastborns.Popular wisdom says that the youngest ? who never quite shakes the role of being the baby of the family ? tends to be more free-spirited, adventurous, risky, and creative.Youngest siblings often don?t have as many care-taking responsibilities and may have more freedom to do things their own way.While lastborns may be charming, they also have the potential to be manipulative, spoiled or babied to the point of helplessness."The last born is the one who will probably still have a pet name although he's 29 and has a masters degree," Leman says.A lastborn who comes into a pack of already straight-and-narrow siblings might carve out her own niche by being more spunky and daring.

About:
Hi, my name is Tessa (you can call me Tess if you so choose) and I'm on this website to dig into my soul, man. Sort of. I'm a young 'un in the midst of high school. I'm going to be a writer when I'm older. (Though I'm technically one now, just not a *published* one.) One should note that in this I haven't necessarily guaranteed to be a SUCCESSFUL one, per se, but I certainly hope so, dude. 
However, with my arcane grammar knowledge (HEIL WEBSTER*), head full of ideas, and 100+ WPM, it seems that this is my fate; I feel most comfortable sitting at home, tinkering away on my laptop in a caffeinated daze while the rest of the world carries on with their business. That's just the way it is.  
I guess I don't really need to explain much about my personality, because I'm sure at this point you already know that I'm an eccentric, creative dreamer. But you won't know that I love cats and stuffed animals or that I enjoy playing the trombone.  And all animals, really are the bomb, except I don't really like bombs because they're all destructive and stuff. 
However, you probably could guess that I admire bassoons, and the flaming is in reference to their inherent coolness, not my secret desire to set them aflame and dance around the burning wood laughing maniacally. Did I just say that aloud? Freudian slip! (Flaming doesn't, incidentally, refer to a flamboyant gay man, although a gay bassoon is well within the realms of possibility because like, in German they're called "fagotts" or something, nuff said, plus you're blowing into a giant thing of wood. Homoerotic much?!?!?) 
On a related note, Freud is a really weird guy. Sure, he did set up the basis for modern psychology, but he was really weird. What's up with the Oedipus Complex anyway? Gross! At least I can blame his buddy Jung for coming up with the female variant, the Electra Complex. 
But the oboe is just a silly instrument. It's kind of annoying and goose-ish, even when played correctly. Don't tell any oboists that...I know one and they're quite sensitive folk, due to spending a majority of their time carving out wood and soaking it and stuff. I'd be crabby, too, if I was them. But I'm not. I'm a tromboner. (Hehehe boner. I need to stop spending time with 15 year old boys.)
x

I suck at describing myself for the most part so read some nice things my friend says about me because these are facts ;) 
According to my friend;
Unbeknownst to her, she is a very diverse person, consisting of many personality traits. She is humble, goofy, brave, smart, wise, empathetic, and strong. She has faced adversity from a very young age and still has many challenges and struggles that effect her daily. However, she continues to fight and persevere because she is hopeful and goal oriented. 
These experiences have allowed her to develop a fascinating mind that is great at observing and breaking down situations. She is able to weigh all of the information and come to the best solution or the most moral conclusion. And when new information is added, she is completely capable of objectively deducing a new ideal from that additive construct. She is aware of the fact that she isn't perfect and always strives to better herself, as well as others. No matter the situation, she tries to build her friends up. Even when bringing forth a flaw within them, she is deeply concern for their well being and would take any criticisms in stride likewise. 
This is why she is such a wise and intelligent individual. You won't find her setting unrealistic standards for others as well as standards that are above her own.  
She is extremely goofy but in a fun and humorous way. If you're ever feeling down and need a pick-me-up, she's the one to see. She can give advice and empathize with your issues, and help you feel better when it's time to move forward. She has a big heart and anyone would be lucky to have a relationship with her, be it friendship or otherwise. 
She has many interests varying from music, to observation, to anime, learning, cartoons, mystery, and video games. The list goes on. However, she can talk about anything and keep the hype going regardless of the activity or subject. 
She is the girl next door, the moral compass, the wise familiar. She is the model-the blueprint-the template of what we consider a respectable and admirable human being. You will never feel unappreciated, forgotten or worthless when in her presence, because she is your devoted rock who is more patient and reliable than most. She makes the room brighter and your heart lighter. She is and will always be a kindred spirit.
If your interested feel free to message me!

I was hatched from a beautiful gray egg in the dead of night, in the light of a full moon, in the stinking humidity of a Texas' summer breath, and the first thing I did was release a terrifying scream that shook the surrounding earth within a radius of 5 miles. Naturally, it shook me out of the tree and I landed on my head. Ever since then I just haven't been right. 
I was taken in by a family of wolves that had been roving around for a nice armadillo to snack on. They had thought it was me and proceeded to start chewing me, but I had the consistency of stringy melting rubber ball and they spit me out declaring I was the nastiest thing they've ever tasted. From that day forward I was a wolf. Everything they did, I was expected to do. Whatever they ate, I ate. Whatever they played, and bounced among them. Wherever they went, I waddled along right behind them. 
With time, I grew. Not much, but I did grow in many ways. My wiry body grew thicker and sharper. My fur turned into long, sleek feathers, which was worth the awkward bald patches I was heckled for for so long. My beak became hard, my claws sharp, my eyes keen. Though mainly innate, a large part of my wit was also strengthened by my little pack. We shared the desire to hunt, but they piqued my interest in not just tactics, but true strategy. How intrinsic I became when we discovered I was creature of flight. I wasn't an odd thing for me however, to smash my cranium into the nearest pine and send its bulky seeds scattering all over my brothers and send the prey running. In time though, I was soaring high and providing a good eye to my fellow hunters. Ah, the joy that floods back when I think of us all gathered around a slain doe, them ripping into the meat, me giving an occasional good tear with my hardy beak and leaning back to gulp it all down at once. Those days couldn't last forever though. 
One morning I had came across a curious little hole, so I shuffled around it and peered in. I didn't see anything inside so I paced around it five more times while looking around then stopped, looked down, then peered in again. Well, there was still nothing to see but the hole was beckoning me. So I stuck my head in it. 
It really wasn't the best decision to say the least, my head became stuck. I looked around a bit inside and shortly after realized I couldn't pull it back out. I pulled and twisted and shoved back and forth over and over. I screamed and cried and from the outside I'm sure it looked like a strange mating dance. So much time went by and I finally just relaxed all my muscles and let my body collapse outside the hole. My eyes started closing and right when I was about to completely doze off, something started sniffing my butt; but I recognize that snout anywhere--it was the very cub I had grown up with all these years--Snoofy! I cried out in joy and he bit my butt to my alarm. "You know me!" "I can't get you out any other way!" With that he continued tugging and pulling my body every which way. He then tried digging around me, dirt kept collapsing on my head but the ground was becoming loose.  
Suddenly a shout ran out and I heard a growl. Somebody screamed and something hit Snoofy, he let out a yelp and collapsed on my legs. Again, I was alone, ants picking my skin, a soaking wet butt with clumps of dirt from Snoofy's attempt to free me.  I heard more steps behind me. Little smooth hands picked dirt around and pulled
me out. I was happy to be free, but not to be in the clutches of a little human but I was helpless. I was weak and somewhat bent up, my eyes half open due to tears and chunks of dirt stuck in them. I could barely see the girl even with evening fast approaching.  
Somehow I ended up in her backpack, in a house, in an animal shelter, in a pile of balloons, on a cruise, and halfway around the world. She was nice as well as my other captors--but they had their own ends and I had to find my pack. I've since escaped my rescuer and others too, I've zipped through power lines and fought rats with sharp claws and whips for tails. I've had many good times too, and I've enjoyed my solitary travels more than many I've had with company--but I long for the night when I'm reunited with my pack and we can scream together to the moon.
The world is filled with good people, you just have to look for it within them.

The following description of the 379 was not written by me but taken from: https://www.facebook.com/Katherinefauvreconsulting/posts/1392449044409080 
The 379 
I call the 279 and the 379 the Rainbow Tritypes. They like colorful events, multi-colored images and colorful people. They are diverse and accepting and generally love people. 
These two Tritypes are very similar at first glance. However, the difference between the 3 and the 2 is important. The 279 is the most relational Tritype and the 379 is the most positive Tritype. 379s are even more positive that the 279s. They care about people like the 279 but focus more on their achievements. Both Tritypes avoid conflict and want to be upbeat...but how? 
The 279 needs easy relating and positive encounters...they try to smooth things over so people are happy and easier to be around. ;)) They focus on okness. 
The 379 needs to "be" an exemplar of what is positive. They are like a handful of colorful balloons. They also love images of rainbows and balloons regardless of what type leads. The 3 needs to be positive to be a success in the eyes of others...their can-do nature is motivated by what is positive to be liked. The 7 needs to be upbeat and is motivated by what is possible to be liked.The 9 needs to be comfortable and feels they must be kind and harmonious to be liked. 
So the 379 struggles when they have a disappointing experience and don't achieve their goal. They are quick to deny painful emotions in favor of pseudo happiness and turn lemons into lemonade more than any other Tritype. 
When they are down their world become bleak and gray. It is an opportunity for introspection and growth but for this Tritype it needs to be in small bites. 
So when a painful experience is chronic and needs time to heal the 379 can become impatient and very hard on themselves for being down. Like the balloons of happiness that become deflated,when in pain, the 379 can come across as shallow due to their effort to be positive when they are actually feeling despair and a sense of inner emptiness. They can feel like empty calories. 
They love people and the energy that comes from being connected to people. They like color in every form. Like flowers that turn to face the sun, 379s need the inspiration that comes from the positive feedback they receive for being good-natured. They are secretly very ambitious but seek affirmation in a quiet way. 
The 379 Tritype needs to be positive. They lose their motivation to be and become.They want success and to feel upbeat but also seek quiet stardom.

Your core type (your strongest type) is Type 7 with a 6 wing: Type Seven individuals are energetic, engaging, and playful. They have a love for life and can easily jump from one exciting topic to the next. The Type Seven thought process is a bit scattered, but that?s because they are easily interested in many different things. This is why Type Seven is often called The Enthusiast. When in a growth state, Type Sevens become focused like Type Fives. When they?re stressed, they become a perfectionist like a Type One. The enthusiastic nature of the Type Seven combines with the cooperative nature of the Type Six, making the 7w6 a very outgoing type. 
Your second type (your next strongest type) is Type 3 with a 4 wing: Type Three individuals are self-assured, confident, and driven for success. Type Threes have a great deal of energy that propels them to excel at their chosen field, and this is why the type is often called The Achiever. Although Threes may not always like it, they?re often looked up to. Type Threes, more than any other type, are the most likely to be a workaholic. When in a state of growth, Threes become more cooperative and trusting of others, like a Type Six. When stressed, Threes become withdrawn like a Type Nine. You are a Type Three with a Four wing, which means that your energetic nature is tempered by a Four tendency to withdraw, which gives you a sense of calm that others often lack. 
Your third type (the least-used of the three) is Type 8 with a 7 wing: Eights are assertive, dominant individuals who naturally take control of situations. Eights are aggressive in satisfying their needs, and indeed, Type Eight is the most aggressive personality type in the Enneagram. When in a state of growth, Eights become like Type Twos - caring and protective of other people. When Eights are stressed, they become withdrawn and secretive like Type Fives. You're an Eight with a Seven wing, which means that the outgoing nature of Seven combines with the assertive nature of Type Eight to create one of the most dynamic types in the Enneagram. Type 8w7s are a force to be reckoned with.

This forum and those who upkeep it are hugely beneficial in this process, and for that I am grateful to everyone here. 
My life is currently in limbo. I am waiting to graduate; once I do, I will see if I will go into the corporate world or do something completely unexpected and wild. In the meantime, my mind is overheating. My brain is a pressure cooker full of vague feelings and ideas; once I have the time they will all be released! 
In the past I was a people-pleaser and a materialistic social butterfly. Now I realise that none of these labels suit me, so I am now a gentle soul that appreciates quiet and peace. My heart is full to the brim with empathy and care for others; love beams from my heart to those I have connected with. I wish I could curl up next to them and spend the rest of my life just being near them and enjoying their presence, like a little cat basking contentedly in the sunlight. My spirit is kind but my voice is LOUD about the issues I care about!  I aim to find beauty and meaning in all that I do. I hate writing about myself because i feel self-conscious. I think that personality theories are somewhat pseudo-scientific and should be explored lightly, but I do view them as useful tools for personal advancement and psycho-social understanding. While I feel that theories discussed here have potential to be used in egotistical ways that may be psychologically damaging, I think that the Enneagram is useful in identifying the motivations and poisonous thoughts (as a key founder stated them) that drive people and are particularly helpful for spiritual :P advancement, but in a less concrete way as explained by the overall theory itself, and that the MBTI is valuable in identifying how people interact and view themselves socially. Individuals are immensely more complex than can be explained by a central instinct/fear or guiding 'cognitive function'. Although they should be taken lightly, I do think theories such as the MBTI, Socionics and the Enneagram are nonetheless useful as indicators of personality and (more importantly) as methods of understanding psychological problems, and I am grateful that places like personalitycafe exist as open and understanding arenas of exploration in the human psyche.

Or if I act, or fail to act, in the manner of your design for action, please let me be. 
I do not, for the moment at least, ask you to understand me. That will come only when you are willing to give up trying to change me into a copy of you.

And one day, perhaps, in trying to understand me, you might come to prize my differences, and, far from seeking to change me, might preserve and even cherish those differences.

It's always changing, morphing, merging, growing, dying. It's the way people try not to change that's unnatural. The way we cling to what things were instead of letting things be what they are. The way we cling to old memories instead of forming new ones. The way we insist on believing despite every scientific indication that anything in this lifetime is permanent. Change is constant. How we experience change that's up to us. It can feel like death or it can feel like a second chance at life. If we open our fingers, loosen our grips, go with it, it can feel like pure adrenaline. I don't care about socializing with a lot of people if I find them to be some sort of incompetent fool or I'm just awkward around them because I'm not comfortable around them; either one of those two or it's just that no one around cares to talk about things I enjoy discussing.  
I am a pretty accepting and understanding person for the most part, but this does NOT mean I am going to accept everything someone says or does. Also, this does not mean that I am going to be accepting of everyone. What this means is that I am open to others' views if they're credible to me. It is all about HOW you present your views to me, not so much WHAT your views are. So, if you find yourself wondering why I turned your views away without question or am "being stubborn and not listening to your so called 'wisdom'", you can count on that being why.  
I like arguing for the sakes of arguing! This is because I can be a competitive person. No, I?m not all into physical competition but rather I like intellectual discussions or even debates? as long as I know what the hell I?m talking about in regards to the topic at hand (and related things of course).  
If there's one thing that REALLY sickens me about people the most, it's short-sightedness. Again, everyone slips up here and there, perhaps they will do something impulsive or just downright idiotic; even I don't always think things through all the way (no one does 100% of the time). Those who just can't think about the future at all are the ones that I just can't get along with one bit. Even though I like to think of past memories, I LOVE to ponder about the possibilities, and in that the future a lot more than I show/discuss.  
One day, I want to invent something that will improve the quality of life for the human population (I have some ideas that I don't want to share on here :P). In this, I highly value innovation and creativity because I feel that without those 2 things, we would still be in the stone age to this day and people would still live only until they are 35 years old or so.  
I also value mental competence. Ok, I understand that people, including myself, make silly mistakes and do stupid things; however, if one is intelligent enough, I feel that they will be able to learn from their mistakes and change for the future to prevent further mistakes of similar or the same nature. If you cannot learn from your own mistakes at all or just don?t care to do so, then I do not wish to associate myself with you. In other words, I get uptight with truly stupid people. 
Another thing I highly value in myself along with others is the ability to understand him-or-herself (introspection). When I get to know people, they really should know who they are as a person. It may take some thinking but it?s not really hard to understand why you: are interested in the things you are; are attracted to the people you?re attracted to; why you feel the way you do about some things or why you?re in a particular mood; why you think the way you do; why you perceive things the way you do; etc. 
It really disappoints me when I?m trying to get to know someone by asking questions such as ?why do you like that?? and all they say is ?because I just do?. How do you expect others to know you if you don?t even know you? It?s pretty ridiculous to expect others to understand you if you don?t understand yourself.  
In my personal opinion, lying about who you are/not being yourself is downright pointless to me; if you're lying to protect yourself or someone else, it's one thing (if it?s a good cause done for a good reason). Otherwise, you're lying to yourself in the end.  
I do not respond in a particularly desirable way to others attempting to control me via testing my guilt or fear factors. Many people have tried to control me by trying to place guilt or fear on me and believe me they didn't get the results they liked. I am not one to be controlled anyways, although I can follow rules if they are logical and just make sense to me. As I like to say, others may steer the boat but only I am the captain to my ship. 
Another thing that really bothers me about some people is when they feel the need to use ?sophisticated? vocabulary terms in casual conversation. When I think of socializing with others in a casual setting, you should be on the same page. Save the whole competition thing for circumstances where there is reason to be competitive. If you?re trying to impress others with your vocabulary and thus trying to look more educated than those you are socializing casually with, that to me shows insecurity and shows that person?s inability to hold a real conversation with others. No wonder people don?t like being around those type of people. If you?re like that, no wonder people don?t like you! That?s how I feel about it anyways.   
If/when I find someone I want to be with for the rest of my life or at least a pretty long time, I really do hope that this person knows how to manage their time properly and learns that work/school isn't their whole life. I mean honestly, if you expect someone to understand you care about them and such, make some effort to spend quality time together. I find it so funny when people decide to get married, yet when they spend little time together they wonder why their marriage life sucks so much @$$. 
Also, I need someone who is going to be able to have the time or at least be able to MAKE the time to give me a call not just send a text message or when they know I'm upset to actually tend to me right then and there, not holding onto that thought until they're done with work or school or even a game. I'm sorry but making someone wait for comfort and love is just so loser-like. Just sayin'.

Evil is a Passionate Lover   
Finished with sadness,
I turn my Soul from familiar smells
And Primal comforts.
Fight the overwhelming pull
Of Habit and Time,
perfumed smoke, casual stomping
of unripened worth,
sexual awareness before awareness of sex. 
Come here, child. Learn from me.
Don't lie there and barter dignity for touch,
holiness for a momentary tribute to existence.
Sanctity for seminal fluid, and obstinate callouses. 
Run your mental fingers over the back of my experience.
Feel the welts. Slowly...Yes. Oh,That, that was a bad one. ..
Time has changed their appearance.
But I have changed their effect.
Dwell on the pain but briefly,
for I have high hopes for you, my child. 
Be afraid of evil. It does exist.
Into His eyes I looked .
Inhuman slits of black.
You think I jest?!
When the eyes become coal,
there is no more pleading,
There is no human behind the mask.
The Pain will now commence.
By what machinations?
He swirls up your body like sensuous smoke,
then materializes
with a death grip on your heart.
Evil is a passionate lover. 
Stay away from the bad boys. Keep from dark corners. Mark thy doorpost of chastity bright red. Then, maybe, my sweet child, this angel of death will passover.

Hello, there. The name's Dea (Day-uh), if you don't feel like constantly pronouncing the scientific name of a moth family.  ;) 
Feel free to chat if you'd like. I promise, I'm friendly. Though if you can't handle a bit of weird, you may want to reconsider socializing with me.  
Anyway, I'm here because I've developed a heavy interest in psychological traits and behavior, and enjoy finding ways to connect them. 
One thing I must emphasize about myself-- 
I am never done learning.  
Research is my foundation. I have a heavy obsession with statistics and charts. In this regard, I view it as art, and art, in turn, becomes the artist. This is an unending mutuality.  
I have plenty of other interests too. I love nature and value solitude (to the point that it might as well be a long-term hobby). I also enjoy dissecting and repairing broken electronics. I'm certified in PC repair.  
Hey, we all have that one 'off' interest.  
Though, warning--whatever you have to say to me has the potential to fall victim to a ~90% chance of being over-analyzed, sifted, filtered, and steeped, being saved for that one ridiculously improbable situation I might encounter where what I've learned might actually make a constructive impact while the blatant every-day chance to use it goes over my head while I'm busy with self-reflecting and hermitizing. 
In other words.... my analytical tendency is evil.   
Now that that's out of the way, if you still care to chat, have at it. If you have any questions, ask. Don't be afraid to. I generally answer, but I'd probably die if I had to be the one to initiate the conversation.  
Well, beyond this point, I'm not quite sure what to say, so I'll list some of my favorite quotes:

The ?I? in me, my friend, dwells in the house of silence, and therein it shall remain forever more, unperceived, unapproachable.? -Kahlil Gibran 
"Look like th' innocent flower, But be the serpent under 't." -Macbeth

Like their fellow SPs, ISTPs are fundamentally Performers (note the capital 'P' :-)), but as Ts their areas of interest tend to be mechanical rather than artistic like those of ISFPs, and unlike most ESPs they do not present an impression of constant activity. On the contrary, they lie dormant, saving their energy until a project or an adventure worthy of their time comes along--and then they launch themselves at it. The apparently frenzied state that inevitably ensues is actually much more controlled than it appears--ISTPs always seem to know what they're doing when it comes to physical or mechanical obstacles--but the whole chain of events presents a confusing and paradoxical picture to an outsider.ISTPs are equally difficult to understand in their need for personal space, which in turn has an impact on their relationships with others. They need to be able to "spread out"--both physically and psychologically--which generally implies encroaching to some degree on others, especially if they decide that something of someone else's is going to become their next project. (They are generally quite comfortable, however, with being treated the same way they treat others--at least in this respect.) But because they need such a lot of flexibility to be as spontaneous as they feel they must be, they tend to become as inflexible as the most rigid J when someone seems to be threatening their lifestyle (although they usually respond with a classic SP rage which is yet another vivid contrast to their "dormant," impassive, detached mode). These territorial considerations are usually critical in relationships with ISTPs; communication also tends to be a key issue, since they generally express themselves non-verbally. When they do actually verbalize, ISTPs are masters of the one-liner, often showing flashes of humor in the most tense situations; this can result in their being seen as thick-skinned or tasteless.Like most SPs, ISTPs may have trouble with rote and abstract classroom learning, which tend not to be good measures of their actual intelligence. They tend, sometimes with good reason, to be highly skeptical of its practical value, and often gravitate towards classes in industrial arts; part-time vocational/ technical programs can be useful to even the college-bound ISTP. In terms of careers, mechanics and any of the skilled trades are traditional choices, and those ISTPs with strong numerical as well mechanical gifts tend to do extremely well in most areas of engineering. Working as paramedics or firefighters can fulfill the ISTP need to live on the edge; they are at their best in a crisis, where their natural disregard for rules and authority structures allows them to focus on and tackle the emergency at hand in the most effective way.ISTPs with more sedate careers usually take on high-risk avocations like racing, skydiving, and motorcycling. While aware of the dangers involved, they are so in touch with the physical world that they know they can get away with much smaller safety margins than other types.

About: I'm an INTP and consistently test as such. I'm less interested in the enneagram but I've tested both as a 5w6 and a 9, which means I'm likely the former (in any case, very conflict avoidant). I can see both sides of most arguments, but am dismissive of emotional reasoning except when I can see its relevance. I consider myself extremely skeptical, although I maintain tact and try not to push my opinions on others, but will freely share them when prompted (I have many, but few of them are hardened). This being said, I am also skeptical of Jungian psychology and the like, but from a social perspective I think typology is very useful for understanding possible thought processes and points of view of others. I've decided to join this forum because I find some of the conversations really interesting and am hoping to learn more about how myself and others function in a broad sense, and maybe improve my social skills (I sometimes have trouble with new people).To go over my profile in a bit more detail, I suffer from social anxiety and depression, but am still very much capable of functioning well socially when I am at social gatherings. However, I'm also capable of playing up parts of my personality to be the person certain people will like, so I'm kind of this paradoxically reclusive social chameleon. People really seem to like me, but even when the feeling is mutual I often have difficulty reaching out to them.I am a left-wing, homosexual, cisgendered, agnostic male from southern Ontario. I am the youngest of several siblings, and generally have very mixed emotions about most people, especially my own family members. I am two years into a very happy relationship with an INFJ. I am an awful procrastinator, but usually able to get high grades anyway. Recently, I left my country's top university 2/3 through my BA to pursue a career in welding. I was originally hoping to be a copy editor or librarian, but after meeting people in those fields I could tell I wasn't interested in the stress of competing for very rare positions and then, if successful, constantly fearing my job being declared excess. I like RPGs and music, playing a few instruments privately and singing, and listening to lots of sad indie music, psychedelic rock, funk, and all their offshoots. Theres more I could say, but I shouldn't blather on anymore.Functionally,I fluctuates from slightly to fairly stronger than E.N is consistently quite stronger than ST is slightly to moderately stronger than FP is always extremely higher than J - usually over 90%.

You are a Type 4 with a 5 wing: "The Bohemian"Your trifix is 4w5, 6w5, 1w9.In enneagram theory, you have one type for how you relate to the world (either 8, 9, or 1), one type for how you think (5, 6, 7) and one type for how you see yourself (2, 3, 4.) Your tri-fix contains one number from each of these triads. They are listed in the order of how strongly they present in your personality. Your core type (your strongest type) is Type 4 with a 5 wing: Type Four individuals are intensely emotionally aware, and often retreat to their rich inner world of concepts and ideas. They are the most artistic type in the Enneagram and driven to create their own, unique identity. Type Fours value authenticity highly and express themselves whenever they can. They are one of the most individualistic types in the Enneagram. Type Fours, when in a state of growth, become principled like Type Ones. When stressed, Type Fours can become clingy like an unhealthy Type Two. You are a Type Four with a Five wing, which means that the individualist nature of a Four combines with the cerebral nature of a Five to make you one of the most creative types in the Enneagram.Your second type (your next strongest type) is Type 6 with a 5 wing: Type Six individuals are reliable, committed, and security-oriented. They are natural troubleshooters, and are always aware of potential problems. This makes the Type Six anxious, but the anxiety fuels them to resolve their problems. They can range from loyal to rebellious, depending on where they get their security from ? if the security is from within, they can be very defiant? if it comes from others, they can be very cooperative and devoted. When a Type Six is in a growth state, they become calm like a Type Nine. When they are stressed, they can become arrogant like an unhealthy Type Three. You are a Type Six with a Five wing, which means that the committed nature of the Six combines with the cerebral nature of the Type Five. As a result, you often excel at concrete thinking and troubleshooting.Your third type (the least-used of the three) is Type 1 with a 9 wing: Type One individuals have a very finely tuned sense of right and wrong, and they chart the course of their lives by following a righteous path. This doesn?t have to be religious? it can be any set of principles that the Type One finds ethical. Ones are perfectionists, often setting high standards for themselves and others. Type One may very well be the most noble type in the Enneagram. When a Type One is in a state of growth, they become excited and joyous like a Seven. When a Type One is stressed, they become emotional and overwhelmed like an unhealthy Type 4. You are a Type One with a Nine wing, which means that the righteous traits of a Type One combine with the peaceful nature of the Type Nine to create a very idealistic personality.Some words that describe you: principled, moralistic, perfectionist, self-critical, creative, unique, authentic, emotional, loyal, reliable, anxious, skeptical.

If you're curious, my name mean here and there, or throughout; frequently. It is a first/second declension adverb in Latin that stems from the perfect passive participle of pando, or to spread (outwards)/unfold.In books, its used to allude to that a reference that can be found in various areas of a text. Though passim itself can be used in english on its own, the phrase sic passim (so throughout) is more commonly used in order to indicate that an idea or a word is found in various areas of an author's work. I uh....meant to use sic passim , but forgot to write sic when registering for my account. I had to reload the page a bunch of times since captcha wasn't working correctly (even though I swear I was correct in writing progressive like 10 times! Which in retrospect was horrible both for myself as well as anyone else who identified as an INFP because of it. Let alone actual INFPs who had to live with such awful characterizations!Anyway, I'm rambling. My apologies. If you're actually reading this, you have my compliments. I'm simply a man who wants everyone in my life to be okay. I'm willing to work hard to see that it happens, but the truth I learned a long time ago is that the only person who can save you is yourself. It doesn't stop me from trying, however. I'm also an animal lover. I've been around livestock (particularly cattle) all of my life. No, I don't eat beef. I've seen too many animals I cared for deeply pass in unpleasant ways (despite my best efforts; such is the brutal truth of farm life, I'm afraid) and have no desire to eat beef as a result. I do, however, really really really love cheese. A lot. Honestly, want to get me started rambling again? Ask me something cheese-esque.Where was I?Oh, anyway, I was featured in an NPR piece on Millenials last year. Even got to close out the radio segment with a quote I gave. It made me feel rather special, though horribly embarrassed by how much I heard my voice quiver. What can I say? I'm a raging perfectionist, especially when it's myself involved.I occasionally blog, though not as often as I like. I also tweet quite regularly. Facebook concerns me, what with the violation of basic privacies and all that. Someday I plan on ruling the world just long enough to take brutal and efficient revenge on everyone and everything that hurt those that I care about, or those who hurt or abuse the poor or weak. 3w2-7w8-9w8The following description of the 379 was not written by me but taken from: https://www.facebook.com/Katherinefauvreconsulting/posts/1392449044409080The 379I call the 279 and the 379 the Rainbow Tritypes. They like colorful events, multi-colored images and colorful people. They are diverse and accepting and generally love people.These two Tritypes are very similar at first glance. However, the difference between the 3 and the 2 is important. The 279 is the most relational Tritype and the 379 is the most positive Tritype. 379s are even more positive that the 279s. They care about people like the 279 but focus more on their achievements. Both Tritypes avoid conflict and want to be upbeat...but how?The 279 needs easy relating and positive encounters...they try to smooth things over so people are happy and easier to be around. ) They focus on okness.The 379 needs to "be" an exemplar of what is positive. They are like a handful of colorful balloons. They also love images of rainbows and balloons regardless of what type leads. The 3 needs to be positive to be a success in the eyes of others...their can-do nature is motivated by what is positive to be liked. The 7 needs to be upbeat and is motivated by what is possible to be liked.The 9 needs to be comfortable and feels they must be kind and harmonious to be liked.So the 379 struggles when they have a disappointing experience and don't achieve their goal. They are quick to deny painful emotions in favor of pseudo happiness and turn lemons into lemonade more than any other Tritype.When they are down their world become bleak and gray. It is an opportunity for introspection and growth but for this Tritype it needs to be in small bites.So when a painful experience is chronic and needs time to heal the 379 can become impatient and very hard on themselves for being down. Like the balloons of happiness that become deflated,when in pain, the 379 can come across as shallow due to their effort to be positive when they are actually feeling despair and a sense of inner emptiness. They can feel like empty calories.They love people and the energy that comes from being connected to people. They like color in every form. Like flowers that turn to face the sun, 379s need the inspiration that comes from the positive feedback they receive for being good-natured. They are secretly very ambitious but seek affirmation in a quiet way.The 379 Tritype needs to be positive.
